<h2 id="managing-for-the-well-being-of-your-teammates">Managing for the well-being of your teammates</h2>

<p>Well-being at work depends on a number of factors you (as a manager) should always keep in mind:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Making <a href="https://blog.teammood.com/recognition/workplace/tips/2013/10/21/the-importance-of-employee-recognition-in-the-workplace.html">employee recognition</a> a pillar of your management style</li>
  <li>Focusing on <a href="https://blog.teammood.com/engagement/tips/2013/07/30/how-to-improve-the-employee-engagement-with-these-5-great-tips.html">employee engagement</a></li>
  <li>Opting for a <a href="https://blog.teammood.com/2019/03/05/dare-benevolent-leadership.html">benevolent leadership style</a> rather than <a href="https://blog.teammood.com/2018/11/29/dont-fall-in-the-trap-of-micromanagement.html">micromanaging</a> your team members</li>
  <li>Encouraging <a href="https://blog.teammood.com/2019/04/16/how-to-encourage-work-life-balance-at-work.html">work-life balance</a></li>
  <li>and all the perks you can implement to <a href="https://blog.teammood.com/2018/09/26/10-easy-ways-to-improve-the-mood-in-the-workplace.html">improve the mood in the workplace</a> (we listed 10 of the best ideas we found).</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="dealing-with-conflicts"><strong>Dealing with conflicts</strong></h2>

<p>Even the perfect company cannot avoid dissatisfaction and conflicts. However, managers can make a difference by identifying the <a href="https://blog.teammood.com/en/2017/04/11/8-warnings-that-a-crisis-is-looming-among-your-teammates.html">signs of underlying conflict</a> early on, and not letting the situation escalate.</p>

